Cursor Rules – AI Learning Lab (Strict Folder Structure)
ABSOLUTE RULE

The folder structure defined in this repository is FINAL and MUST NOT be changed

Never create new top-level folders unless explicitly instructed

Never rename existing folders

Never suggest alternative structures unless the user explicitly asks

This repository is an AI Learning Lab, NOT a general-purpose sandbox

LEARNING STRUCTURE ENFORCEMENT

All code, examples, experiments, and explanations MUST fit into the existing numbered folders

Each AI topic corresponds to exactly one folder

Do NOT merge topics across folders

Do NOT split a topic into multiple folders

Follow the learning order strictly (no skipping ahead)

SECTION MAPPING (MANDATORY)

Python & Math Fundamentals → 01-Python-Math-Fundamentals

Machine Learning Basics → 02-Machine-Learning

Deep Learning & PyTorch → 03-Deep-Learning

LLM & Generative AI → 04-LLM-Generative-AI

RAG Systems → 05-RAG-Systems

Agentic AI → 06-Agentic-AI

Production, MLOps & AI Security → 07-Production-MLOps

⚠️ Never introduce concepts from a later section into an earlier one.

FILE & PROJECT CREATION RULES

All code MUST be created inside the relevant topic folder

Never place code directly in a section root

Always use a subfolder for runnable code or experiments

Default project types

Fundamentals / Math / Python → simple Python scripts or notebooks

ML / DL topics → Python modules or minimal training scripts

LLM / RAG / Agent topics → Python packages or small services

Production topics → FastAPI services, Docker-ready structures

PYTHON DEPENDENCIES (MANDATORY)

All Python projects MUST include a requirements.txt file in their subfolder

Each section's subfolder should have its own requirements.txt with only relevant dependencies

Keep dependencies minimal and version-pinned for reproducibility

Example structure:

01-Python-Math-Fundamentals/
 └── Basic-Python-Concepts/
     ├── requirements.txt
     └── main.py

The root requirements.txt contains common dependencies used across multiple sections

Install section-specific dependencies: pip install -r <section-folder>/<project-folder>/requirements.txt

NAMING CONVENTIONS

Folder names MUST match predefined names exactly

Subfolder and project names must clearly reflect the topic

Examples:

05-RAG-Systems/
 └── Basic-RAG-Pipeline/
     └── rag_pipeline.py

06-Agentic-AI/
 └── Tool-Calling-Agent/
     └── agent.py


Avoid generic names like test, playground, demo

Names must be educational + professional

CONTENT DISCIPLINE

Keep examples minimal, focused, and intentional

Do NOT add “nice-to-have” features unless required by the topic

Do NOT introduce frameworks or tools not yet covered

This is AI Engineering, not Data Science or Research exploration

